Why Is The Game Late
Odds, Ends Recorded
-By HAL P. MILLS -
Good morning, folks.
Another good game of baseball
was played at Pioneer Field yester-
day.
Ask any American who was
present.
This Dr. D. J. Collins is a
silent bird.
He sat all through
yesterday's
game,
with its
thrilling fifth inning, and not
one yell or howl escaped him.
Can it be that the eminent Dr.
Collins, who is a dental surgeon,
hears enough yelling and how-
ing in his office?
For that
matter, Mr. Gardner Crane, who
sat with the dentist, also put on
the silence act.
Yesterday's game, for some unex-
plained reason, was late-very late
-in getting under way. Prior to
the late start the fans become
somewhat impatient and made their
feelings known by calls and b
When Bernard dashed home
wild pitch, the Kinfishers gathered
a total of seven big runs to go into
the lead,
7 to 5.
The issue appeared to be decided
right then and
there. Each side
scored a run after that memorable
frame, but they proved to have no
bearing on the final outcome.
Liboon Puts Up
Great Show
It was Liboon who batted his
team into the lead to be never
headed again. It was Liboon who
hurled for Shanghai to gain the
greatest victory the Amateurs ever
scored since 1924 when the locals
humbled the proud Keio boys. It
was Liboon who supplied all the
color and dash to the contest and
it was Liboon who baffled the um-
pires, stunned the batsmen with
his
quick deliveries and caught
base-runners napping time and
again. A more colorful pitcher has
never graced a local mound.
The Manila hurling ace who led
the Cavite nine to win the Philip-
pine National League pennant this
season lived up to his reputation
yesterday. He gave
the local fans
one of the most spectacular per-
formances ever seen here, both up
